<td class="article-body"><DIV class=newsHead><STRONG>Safin Romps Over Rochus</STRONG></DIV>by Neil Schlecht<BR><I>Monday, September 4, 2006</I><BR>
<P>On the heels of his five-set upset of No. 4 seed David Nalbandian, Marat Safin took on his longtime nemesis, Olivier Rochus of Belgium. On a packed Grandstand court, Safin played the kind of imposing, intimidating tennis the big man is capable of and stormed past his diminutive opponent, 6-3, 6-2, 6-3, in just 90 minutes.</P>
<P>Rochus entered the match the higher ranked player, as the unseeded Safin, a former champion here, has plummeted to No. 104 in the world. The 5-foot-4 Rochus, who has a reputation as a giant killer, has bedeviled the 6-foot-4 Safin on several occasions, including two victories on fast courts earlier this year (though the Russian held a 5-4 career advantage coming into this third-round encounter). </P>
<P>While it’s unusual in today’s power game for such a vertically challenged player to excel, Rochus, the 26th seed here, has a solid all-court game, and he moves and retrieves well. Ultimately, though, he has few weapons with which to hurt an opponent like Safin, who brings so much more heat on his serve and groundstrokes. </P>
<P>Safin played the cleanest and most controlled tennis he has played all year, making few unforced errors and painting the lines with heavy backhands and forehands. The Russian smacked huge first serves and used his high-bouncing second delivery—one second-ball ace appeared to bounce right over Rochus’s head—to keep his opponent off balance. </P>
<P>In the first set, Safin set the tone for the match by simply outgunning Rochus. At 3-5, Safin rocketed a crosscourt backhand to earn a set point, and he broke serve and snatched the set with another thunderous backhand down the line. </P>
<P>In the second, Safin continued with pinpoint accuracy. Serving at 2-2, the Russian blasted three aces and one service winner. Again he employed his smooth and potent backhand, smoking consecutive winners past Rochus to break him and go up 4-2. An insurance break came on yet another backhand service return down the line, and Safin was up two-sets-to-none in just 58 minutes. </P>
<P>Rochus was so bamboozled that he started the third set on the wrong side of the net. With a wry smile, Safin motioned him to the opposite side of the court. </P>
<P>A momentary lapse in the third set was the only blip on the day for Safin. He lost his concentration and serve early, with a sudden spate of errors coming off his racket, but he quickly righted things, broke back and proceeded to run away with the match. </P>
<P>Safin advances to the fourth round here, in his first appearance at the US Open since 2004, to play No. 14 seed Tommy Haas, a winner in five over Robby Ginepri. </P><BR clear=left>
